There is apparently no reason why the liability of masters for their slaves’ delicts in general (Tit. 8 inf.) and of owners of animals for damage done by thern (Tit. 9) should not be considered quasi-delictual, for it was enforced by special actions, which were at least as penal as that against the judge ‘qui litem suam fecerit! The fact seems to be that the cases mentioned in this Title are intended only as examples of quasi· delicts, and that the other two would naturally have found a place among rhem but for Justinian’s inveterate habit of following the arrange- ment of Gaius. As the latter does not treat quasi-delict at all, he discusses the liability of masters and fathers for the delicts of their slaves and children in power in close connection with a cognate question -their liability upon their contracte ; so that Justinian, in his anxiety to adhere to the latter arrangement, has committed a fault of classification.
